<subSubSection id="F9AAF8E2075DFFA92DF9ED237813FA8A" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9ED237F93FBEA" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DF9ED237D17FCEF" bold="true" box="[199,321,798,823]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Species in this genus are characterized by (1) frontoparietals, one, (2) supraciliaries, five, (3) supraoculars, four, as reported in original description (
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92E33ED7F7F9AFC82" author="Andersson" box="[781,972,834,858]" firstAuthor="Andersson" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref168196" refString="Andersson, L. G. (1918) New lizards from South America. Arkiv for Zoologi, 11, 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1918">Andersson 1918</bibRefCitation>
), but supraoculars were not reported by Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DC0ED5A7D6FFCA6" box="[254,313,870,894]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
(2009), (4) prefrontal contact, present, (5) parietal contact, present, (6) rows of nuchals, 2–3, (7) dorsals + ventrals, undetermined (46–58 dorsals and 30–47 ventrals as reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92907EDB7797CFC7A" author="Miralles" box="[1081,1322,906,931]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Miralles" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="47 - 68" refId="ref175771" refString="Miralles, A., Chaparro, J. C. &amp; Harvey, M. B. (2009 a) Three rare and enigmatic South American skinks. Zootaxa, 2012, 47 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009" yearSuffix="a">
Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA929A0EDB67880FC7B" box="[1182,1238,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
, 2009a
</bibRefCitation>
, but those counts were made using a different counting method than used here), (8) total lamellae, not reported, (9) a dark middorsal stripe, absent, (10) dark dorsolateral stripes, absent, (11) a dark lateral stripe, present, and (12) dark ventral striping, absent. Body size was not reported by Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92E48EDCA7FE6FBD6" box="[886,944,1014,1038]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
(2009), but 
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA9297EEDCB795DFBD6" author="Andersson" box="[1088,1291,1014,1038]" firstAuthor="Andersson" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 9" refId="ref168196" refString="Andersson, L. G. (1918) New lizards from South America. Arkiv for Zoologi, 11, 1 - 9." type="journal article" year="1918">Andersson (1918)</bibRefCitation>
noted in the original description that the largest specimen was 
<quantity id="7648068C075DFFA92FF9EA277F40FBEA" box="[711,790,1050,1074]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" unit="mm" value="60.0">60 mm</quantity>
SVL (
<tableCitation id="FC329ED2075DFFA92E5EEA277FEEFBEA" box="[864,952,1050,1074]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="29.[151,241,690,714]" captionText="TABLE 2. Taxonomic summary for lizards of the Subfamily Mabuyinae. For each genus, the number of species, occurrence on islands, and sample size, are shown along with the primary diagnostic characters used in distinguishing the genera. See individual accounts for additional diagnostic characters specific to each genus. Sample size is listed separately (in parentheses) for total lamellae. Sample size indicates specimens examined, except for Orosaura and Exila where data are from the literature (see accounts). N = no, Y = yes. Rare or uncommon states given in parentheses." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9EA037FAAFAF6" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
Having a single (fused) frontoparietal separates 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92FD8EA037F77FB8E" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[742,801,1086,1110]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Exila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FD8EA037F77FB8E" box="[742,801,1086,1110]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Exila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
