<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92F07EAF27EC6FB3E" box="[569,656,1231,1254]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Panopa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92FA0EAF37F78FB3E" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[670,814,1230,1254]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Psychosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FA0EAF37F78FB3E" box="[670,814,1230,1254]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Psychosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92E53EAF37FAFFB3E" authorityName=", Fitzinger" authorityYear="1826" box="[877,1017,1230,1254]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Spondylurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92E53EAF37FAFFB3E" box="[877,1017,1230,1254]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Spondylurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is distinguished by the absence of dark dorsolateral stripes. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92FB1EACE7F78FAD3" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[655,814,1267,1291]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Brasiliscincus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FB1EACE7F78FAD3" box="[655,814,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Brasiliscincus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92E7BEACE7F97FAD3" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[837,961,1267,1291]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Capitellum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92E7BEACE7F97FAD3" box="[837,961,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Capitellum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92EE7EACE7828FAD3" authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1845" box="[985,1150,1267,1291]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Copeoglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92EE7EACE7828FAD3" box="[985,1150,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Copeoglossum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA929A8EACE7957FAD3" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[1174,1281,1267,1291]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Manciola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA929A8EACE7957FAD3" box="[1174,1281,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Manciola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92826EACE79C2FAD3" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[1304,1428,1267,1291]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Maracaiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92826EACE79C2FAD3" box="[1304,1428,1267,1291]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Maracaiba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92DA9EB2B7D70FAF6" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,294,1302,1326]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Notomabuya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DA9EB2B7D70FAF6" box="[151,294,1302,1326]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Notomabuya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92C0AEB2B7DF6FAF6" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[308,416,1302,1326]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Orosaura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92C0AEB2B7DF6FAF6" box="[308,416,1302,1326]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Orosaura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92CE3EB2A7E7FFAF6" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[477,553,1303,1326]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Varzea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92CE3EB2A7E7FFAF6" box="[477,553,1303,1326]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Varzea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having more than one pair of nuchals.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9EB077813FA8A" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" box="[199,1093,1338,1363]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DF9EB077D78FA8B" bold="true" box="[199,302,1338,1363]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="1">Content.</emphasis>
A single species is placed in this genus: 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92FC6EB067F84FA8B" baseAuthorityName="Andersson" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[760,978,1339,1363]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Exila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigropalmata">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FC6EB067F84FA8B" box="[760,978,1339,1363]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Exila nigropalmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation id="FC329ED2075DFFA92EDEEB077862FA8A" box="[992,1076,1338,1362]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="22.[151,241,1290,1314]" captionText="TABLE 1. Classification of lizards of the Family Mabuyidae, Subfamily Mabuyinae (61 species). Additional details on distribution are provided in the text." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F9AAF8E2075DFFA92DF9EB637FDCFA42" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9EB637FDCFA42" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DF9EB637D36FAAF" bold="true" box="[199,352,1374,1399]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="1">Distribution.</emphasis>
This genus is distributed in the Western Amazonian Basin and on the eastern slopes of the Andes, in 
<collectingCountry id="C9A7EBF9075DFFA92C37EBBF7D08FA42" box="[265,350,1410,1434]" name="Bolivia" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="C9A7EBF9075DFFA92C54EBBF7DE7FA42" box="[362,433,1410,1434]" name="Brazil" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="C9A7EBF9075DFFA92CD5EBBE7E48FA42" box="[491,542,1411,1434]" name="Peru" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92F13EBBF7F4CFA42" author="Miralles" box="[557,794,1410,1435]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Miralles" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="47 - 68" refId="ref175771" refString="Miralles, A., Chaparro, J. C. &amp; Harvey, M. B. (2009 a) Three rare and enigmatic South American skinks. Zootaxa, 2012, 47 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009" yearSuffix="a">
Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FADEBBE7E9AFA43" box="[659,716,1411,1435]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
2009a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="298BB7EC075DFFA92E1BEBBF7F2BFA42" box="[805,893,1410,1434]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1798,1821]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,308,1771]" captionTargetId="figure-88@25.[151,1436,301,1777]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 8. Distribution of the 16 genera of Neotropical skinks, Family Mabuyidae, Subfamily Mabuyinae. (A) Genera occurring in the greater Caribbean region. (B) Genera occurring exclusively in South America. (C) Additional genera occurring in South America, including one with representatives on Caribbean islands." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F9AAF8E2075DFFA92DF9EB9A7964FA3A" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9EB9A7964FA3A" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DF9EB9A7D18FA67" bold="true" box="[199,334,1447,1471]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name (
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92F7DEB9B7E28FA66" authorityName="Hedges &amp; Conn" authorityYear="2012" box="[579,638,1446,1470]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Exila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92F7DEB9B7E28FA66" box="[579,638,1446,1470]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Exila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is a feminine noun derived from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92832EB9B7911FA66" box="[1292,1351,1446,1470]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">exilis</emphasis>
(lean), alluding to the thin body shape and unusually low number of midbody scale rows in this species (24–28).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F9AAF8E2075DFFA92DF9EBD279DEF907" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B10FAB69075DFFA92DF9EBD279DEF907" blockId="84.[151,1436,762,1759]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DF9EBD27D6DF9DF" bold="true" box="[199,315,1519,1543]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
The single species placed in this genus, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92FC1EBD37F8EF9DE" baseAuthorityName="Andersson" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[767,984,1518,1542]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Exila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigropalmata">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FC1EBD37F8EF9DE" box="[767,984,1518,1542]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Exila nigropalmata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was found to be a unique and divergent lineage in published molecular phylogenies (
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92FB3E82F7F2CF9F2" author="Miralles" box="[653,890,1554,1579]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Miralles" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="47 - 68" refId="ref175771" refString="Miralles, A., Chaparro, J. C. &amp; Harvey, M. B. (2009 a) Three rare and enigmatic South American skinks. Zootaxa, 2012, 47 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009" yearSuffix="a">
Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92FCDE82E7F7AF9F3" box="[755,812,1555,1579]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
2009a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92EBBE82F78FBF9F2" author="Miralles &amp; Carranza" box="[901,1197,1554,1578]" firstAuthor="Miralles" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="857 - 869" refId="ref175724" refString="Miralles, A. &amp; Carranza, S. (2010) Systematics and biogeography of the Neotropical genus Mabuya, with special emphasis on the Amazonian skink Mabuya nigropunctata (Reptilia, Scincidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 54, 857 - 869." type="journal article" year="2010">Miralles &amp; Carranza 2010</bibRefCitation>
) and in our tree (
<figureCitation id="298BB7EC075DFFA92850E82F7CF1F996" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1880,1903]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,562,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-175@16.[151,1436,553,1829]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 5 (continued on the next page)" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Its phylogenetic position has not yet been firmly established among the various generic clades (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92DA9E8667D6AF9AB" authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1845" box="[151,316,1627,1651]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Copeoglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92DA9E8667D6AF9AB" box="[151,316,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Copeoglossum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="76B0D0EA075DFFA92C6CE8667D88F9AB" authorityName=", Fitzinger" authorityYear="1826" box="[338,478,1627,1651]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Spondylurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92C6CE8667D88F9AB" box="[338,478,1627,1651]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Spondylurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Its possession of a unique mix of characters (one frontoparietal, contact of prefrontals, multiple nuchals, five supraciliaries, no dark dorsolateral stripes, high number of toe-IV lamellae, and thin body shape) separate it from all other genera. Recently collected material (
<bibRefCitation id="D521D698075DFFA92975E89F7913F962" author="Miralles" box="[1099,1349,1698,1723]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Miralles" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="47 - 68" refId="ref175771" refString="Miralles, A., Chaparro, J. C. &amp; Harvey, M. B. (2009 a) Three rare and enigmatic South American skinks. Zootaxa, 2012, 47 - 68." type="journal article" year="2009" yearSuffix="a">
Miralles 
<emphasis id="83C4777B075DFFA92988E89E78A5F963" box="[1206,1267,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">et al.</emphasis>
2009a
</bibRefCitation>
) added knowledge to the systematics, distribution, and natural history of this otherwise poorly known species and genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
